Furthermore, several cybersecurity reports and honeypot analyses specifically identify "345gs5662d34" as a frequently attempted password in SSH brute-force attacks. For instance, a honeypot recorded it as the most commonly tested password for the username "root". Another study noted the prevalence of "3245gs5662d34" and its variant "345GS5662d34" across various honeypots globally, highlighting them as "unique passwords". It has also been identified as a password used by Polycom CX600 IP phones.

Although primarily recognized as a password, "345gs5662d34" has occasionally been observed being used as a username in automated brute-force attempts, often attributed to "sloppy bots" or scripts that might incorrectly enter password strings into the username field. However, its structure and frequent appearance in password attempt lists strongly suggest its intended role as a password."""
